	  <title>Linear Equations with no Solutions</title>
	  <caption>Linear Equations with no Solutions</caption>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>If a system of linear equations has no solution, then the solution hyperplanes of its equations have no point in common.</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>
               <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                  <img src="ims/ThreeEqnsR2Overdetermined.gif"/>
               </media>
            </para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>There is exactly one way in which the RREF of the system indicates that there is no solution: The RREF contains a leading <math>
                  <latex>1</latex>
               </math> in its augmented part.</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>
					
\begin{array}{ccccccccccccccc|c}
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; 0 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; 0 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; 0 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; 0 \\
\vdots &amp;   &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots \\
\vdots &amp;   &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots \\
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; * &amp; ***    &amp; * &amp; 0 \\
{\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}\dots} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}\dots} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}\dots} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}\dots} &amp; {\color{red}0} &amp; {\color{red}1} \\
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
\end{array}
					
				</latex>
			      </math.display>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>Why does the above system have no solution? â€“ To see this we only need to recall that a row with a leading <math>
                  <latex>1</latex>
               </math> in its augmented part corresponds to an equation in the reduced system of the form:</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>
					
\begin{array}{cccccccccc}
\colorbox{lightgreen}{$0$}{\color{red}x_1} &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$0$}{\color{red}x_2} &amp; + &amp; \cdots &amp; \cdots &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$0$}{\color{red}x_n} &amp; = &amp; {\color{red}1} \\
\end{array}
					
				</latex>
			      </math.display>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>The left hand side is always <math>
                  <latex>0</latex>
               </math>, while the right hand side is <math>
                  <latex>1</latex>
               </math>. So this particular equation has no solution. Hence the entire system has no simultaneous solutions. </para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
